You literally have
to dig for water

00:21:36.594 --> 00:21:38.129
in the dry river beds.

00:21:38.129 --> 00:21:40.598
So through the funds
that they get from tourism

00:21:40.598 --> 00:21:42.934
they're able to do such things

00:21:42.934 --> 00:21:44.669
and have more access to water.

00:21:44.669 --> 00:21:46.170
Education is key.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:48.940
Sending their children to school
is a big thing for them.

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:50.241
Now they are able to do that

00:21:50.241 --> 00:21:52.577
through the benefits
they get from tourism.

00:21:52.577 --> 00:21:53.845
Boyd: And they make
that connection

00:21:53.845 --> 00:21:55.446
between the lions programs
you're doing the Ewaso...

00:21:55.446 --> 00:21:56.280
Shivani: They do.

00:21:56.714 --> 00:21:58.984
Boyd: and the education they're
getting is because of the lions?

00:21:58.984 --> 00:22:00.118
Shivani: Absolutely, yeah.
So we've got

00:22:00.118 --> 00:22:01.786
a great relationship
with the tourism,

00:22:01.786 --> 00:22:04.122
managements and lodges
within our area.

00:22:04.122 --> 00:22:05.690
We work closely
together so people

00:22:05.690 --> 00:22:08.093
can really understand
the relationship between

00:22:08.093 --> 00:22:11.496
tourist and conservation and
working with communities.

00:22:11.496 --> 00:22:12.931
And they have seen that.

00:22:12.931 --> 00:22:14.766
Boyd: And you've got
the Samburu Warriors

00:22:14.766 --> 00:22:16.100
who are walking around
to see

00:22:16.100 --> 00:22:17.702
where the lions are,
warning the people,

00:22:17.702 --> 00:22:19.704
if it's getting close
to their cattle,

00:22:19.704 --> 00:22:21.239
but they're such great trackers.

00:22:21.239 --> 00:22:23.975
Do they also look for
human tracks of poachers?

00:22:23.975 --> 00:22:25.877
Do you have 'em
on the watch for that?

00:22:25.877 --> 00:22:28.013
Shivani: They do, our warriors
are basically out there

00:22:28.013 --> 00:22:30.749
looking out for anything
so not just predators

00:22:30.749 --> 00:22:32.584
but people as well.

00:22:32.584 --> 00:22:35.353
Poaching is a big problem
in our area, northern Kenya.

00:22:35.353 --> 00:22:37.455
So our warriors do
notify the wardens,

00:22:37.455 --> 00:22:41.226
the rangers if they
see any kind of tracks

00:22:41.226 --> 00:22:43.195
that look a little
bit suspicious.

00:22:43.195 --> 00:22:44.896
They're very good
at aging the tracks.

00:22:44.896 --> 00:22:46.064
They know exactly
when that track

00:22:46.064 --> 00:22:47.565
has been through that area.

00:22:47.565 --> 00:22:50.135
They can tell from
the type of shoes who it is.

00:22:50.135 --> 00:22:52.303
They are fantastic trackers
and so they can really

00:22:52.303 --> 00:22:54.872
give information
back to the authorities

00:22:54.872 --> 00:22:56.541
if there's anything that looks

00:22:56.541 --> 00:22:58.443
a little bit suspicious
in that area.

00:22:58.443 --> 00:22:59.511
Boyd: And let's just
