00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:18.629
Now Jack, tell us
how it all started.

00:23:18.629 --> 00:23:21.032
Did you start like
those of us

00:23:21.032 --> 00:23:22.867
who had chemistry sets
when you were a kid,

00:23:22.867 --> 00:23:24.102
blowing up stuff?

00:23:24.102 --> 00:23:25.270
( laughter )

00:23:25.270 --> 00:23:27.738 line:0%
Jack: I started out with
a lot of environmental work

00:23:27.738 --> 00:23:30.374 line:0%
so working with
bioluminescent bacteria

00:23:30.374 --> 00:23:32.110 line:0%
to detect water contaminants.

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:34.612 line:0%
Then I moved on to
like nano ecotoxicity

00:23:34.612 --> 00:23:36.981
so investigate-- I did
one of the first studies

00:23:36.981 --> 00:23:39.417
of its kind on the
impacts of nano particles,

00:23:39.417 --> 00:23:41.553
versus bulk particles
and their impacts

00:23:41.553 --> 00:23:43.487
on the aquatic ecosystems.

00:23:43.487 --> 00:23:45.056
Boyd: I know you have
something that will

00:23:45.056 --> 00:23:46.724
test water quality, what's that?

00:23:46.724 --> 00:23:48.326
Jack: Yeah, yeah, yeah,
so it's essentially

00:23:48.326 --> 00:23:49.727
something the size
of a credit card

00:23:49.727 --> 00:23:52.196
that detects six different
environmental contaminants

00:23:52.196 --> 00:23:54.499
and it's 200,000 times

00:23:54.499 --> 00:23:56.901
less expensive than our
conventional methods.

00:23:56.901 --> 00:23:58.737
And so it cost a dollar
and then also

00:23:58.737 --> 00:24:00.705
one of the very cool things
about it,

00:24:00.705 --> 00:24:03.274
is that it can actually
only take 20 minutes,

00:24:03.274 --> 00:24:04.910
25 minutes to run

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:06.778
and one of the coolest
parts about that project--

00:24:06.778 --> 00:24:08.880
That was kinda like the
minor part of that project.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:12.250
The major part of that
was developing a water filter

00:24:12.250 --> 00:24:14.051
out of recycled
plastic water bottles.

00:24:14.051 --> 00:24:15.553
So essentially you can take
water bottles

00:24:15.553 --> 00:24:17.522
and turn them into filters
that filter out

00:24:17.522 --> 00:24:19.990
95 percent of all heavy
metals and pesticides

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:23.394
in five minutes for 70 cents
and then also

00:24:23.394 --> 00:24:24.895
you can actually put
them in boiling water

00:24:24.895 --> 00:24:26.831
for just one minute
and they will actually

00:24:26.831 --> 00:24:29.267
reclaim up to 90 percent
of those contaminants

00:24:29.267 --> 00:24:30.835
of which you can then
sell back

00:24:30.835 --> 00:24:32.803
and actually profit
from filtering your water.

00:24:32.803 --> 00:24:36.041
So we are currently
still testing with that

00:24:36.041 --> 00:24:38.409
so we do use it for like
heavy metals, pesticides.

00:24:38.409 --> 00:24:40.645
It can also be used for
like fracking contaminants,

00:24:40.645 --> 00:24:43.415
oil spill cleanup and has
a wide variety of usage

00:24:43.415 --> 00:24:45.883
and now I'm moving on
to indoor air quality.

